00:29:28.690 --> 00:29:31.720
But that is interesting.

00:29:31.720 --> 00:29:35.000
As four hashtags,
I think hashtags

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:39.400
aren't quite as a big deal
on social media in China,

00:29:39.400 --> 00:29:44.240
because one, perhaps, because
of language-- not issue,

00:29:44.240 --> 00:29:46.790
but language opportunity.

00:29:46.790 --> 00:29:49.890
Chinese is so much more
compact than English,

00:29:49.890 --> 00:29:52.850
and that each character actually
represents an entire word.

00:29:52.850 --> 00:29:54.690
So 140 characters,
you actually say

00:29:54.690 --> 00:29:56.720
a good amount in 140 characters.

00:29:56.720 --> 00:29:58.390
So you don't really
need hashtags

00:29:58.390 --> 00:30:03.480
as a way of this sort of
reductive meme sort of tool.

00:30:03.480 --> 00:30:05.920
So you're actually able
to say what you want.

00:30:05.920 --> 00:30:08.190
But in Chinese
social media, I think

00:30:08.190 --> 00:30:10.150
images are super powerful.

00:30:10.150 --> 00:30:13.040
Those get circulated so widely.

00:30:13.040 --> 00:30:14.990
Even images of whole essays.

00:30:14.990 --> 00:30:19.520
So you'll often find people
who post-- they'll actually

00:30:19.520 --> 00:30:22.520
type out a 300, 400, 500
characteristic essay--

00:30:22.520 --> 00:30:27.050
sometimes even longer, make
an image of it, and post that.

00:30:27.050 --> 00:30:29.350
And that sort of thing gets
circulated very widely.

00:30:34.848 --> 00:30:36.260
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
anecdote is

00:30:36.260 --> 00:30:39.410
an example of how this cat
and mouse game evolves,

00:30:39.410 --> 00:30:41.790
and you actually have
different tactics being used.

00:30:41.790 --> 00:30:45.620
To what extent does your
research or continued research

00:30:45.620 --> 00:30:49.685
on this indicate that there's
a different way that people

00:30:49.685 --> 00:30:51.940
are trying to post
censored information,

00:30:51.940 --> 00:30:55.317
and that censors are going
to interact with them?

00:30:55.317 --> 00:30:57.650
General question, is you've
got a very rich, descriptive

00:30:57.650 --> 00:31:01.210
account sort of focused on
particular words and themes,

00:31:01.210 --> 00:31:03.250
and you have stories
associated with them.

00:31:03.250 --> 00:31:05.460
To what extent did this
help you anticipate

00:31:05.460 --> 00:31:09.060
what future censorship and
sort of dissident interactions

00:31:09.060 --> 00:31:10.286
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:31:10.286 --> 00:31:11.660
JASON Q. NG: Yeah,
I think what's

00:31:11.660 --> 00:31:15.640
particularly interesting is
how internet users are trying

00:31:15.640 --> 00:31:18.460
to shift away from this sort
of public face in social media.

00:31:18.460 --> 00:31:23.900
So as a lot of folks in
authoritarian societies

00:31:23.900 --> 00:31:27.870
have realized, that
posting material publicly

00:31:27.870 --> 00:31:29.945
is great for
sharing information.

00:31:33.490 --> 00:31:35.840
Sorry, I'll just
repeat the question.

00:31:35.840 --> 00:31:39.360
So the question was about, how
does my research anticipate

00:31:39.360 --> 00:31:42.882
what sort of future
shifts in trends

00:31:42.882 --> 00:31:44.590
will take place in
social media in China.

00:31:47.180 --> 00:31:49.900
So public facing social
media is a great opportunity

00:31:49.900 --> 00:31:51.520
to connect with
folks, but it's also

00:31:51.520 --> 00:31:55.500
an opportunity or a chance
for information controls

00:31:55.500 --> 00:31:56.530
to be placed on it.

00:31:56.530 --> 00:31:58.321
So I think a lot of
folks are shifting away

00:31:58.321 --> 00:32:00.940
from public face in
social media, like Weibo,

00:32:00.940 --> 00:32:04.340
towards more semi-public
or private social media,

00:32:04.340 --> 00:32:08.090
like WeChat, and other
sorts of these chat clients

00:32:08.090 --> 00:32:11.000
that a lot of folks are using
now on their mobile devices.

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:14.160
So in this way, you can still
have thousands of followers

00:32:14.160 --> 00:32:18.040
on WeChat, and you can
blast out posts to them,

00:32:18.040 --> 00:32:20.930
but there's
hopefully no overseer

00:32:20.930 --> 00:32:23.840
sneaking in, and surveilling
your conversation,

00:32:23.840 --> 00:32:25.320
and censoring you,
and potentially

00:32:25.320 --> 00:32:26.520
dragging you to jail.

00:32:26.520 --> 00:32:28.115
So I think that's
one potential shift.

00:32:31.158 --> 00:32:32.699
AUDIENCE: Does your
research give you

00:32:32.699 --> 00:32:34.623
any indication what
portion of the censoring

00:32:34.623 --> 00:32:37.509
is somewhat automated,
and what portion is just

00:32:37.509 --> 00:32:39.430
totally human-made?

00:32:39.430 --> 00:32:40.180
JASON Q. NG: Yeah.

00:32:40.180 --> 00:32:43.200
So the question was,
based on my research,

00:32:43.200 --> 00:32:46.030
do I have a sense of how much
of the censorship is automated,

00:32:46.030 --> 00:32:51.050
and how much of
it is human input?

00:32:51.050 --> 00:32:53.170
I think looking at
my list, I think

00:32:53.170 --> 00:32:55.860
it was fascinating-- especially
to me-- was most fascinating to

00:32:55.860 --> 00:32:57.389
me was the human
element involved.

00:32:57.389 --> 00:32:59.930
Like for instance, you'll notice
that the word Hoobastank was

00:32:59.930 --> 00:33:06.810
blocked on Weibo for some
time, which was weird to me,

00:33:06.810 --> 00:33:08.840
because from what
I know, Hoobastank

00:33:08.840 --> 00:33:13.570
isn't a very politically active
band or music act in China.

00:33:13.570 --> 00:33:16.900
But in fact, what I
think was happening

00:33:16.900 --> 00:33:18.880
there was the
English word, tank,

00:33:18.880 --> 00:33:21.130
which is part of Hoobastank,
was the blocked key word.

00:33:21.130 --> 00:33:23.046
But in fact, when I
searched for the word tank

00:33:23.046 --> 00:33:24.870
at that same time,
"tank" was unblocked,

00:33:24.870 --> 00:33:27.950
and Hoobastank, or maybe the
word stank itself, was blocked.

00:33:27.950 --> 00:33:30.160
So maybe there was
a typo somewhere.

00:33:30.160 --> 00:33:33.495
So these are the sorts of
things that you uncover.

00:33:33.495 --> 00:33:34.870
Other sorts of
research that I've

00:33:34.870 --> 00:33:37.036
done at the Citizen Lab
with collaborators up there,

00:33:37.036 --> 00:33:38.910
we've noticed also
various incidences

00:33:38.910 --> 00:33:41.380
of human censor making mistakes.

00:33:41.380 --> 00:33:46.260
Sometimes they'll uploaded a
list of blacklisted keywords,

00:33:46.260 --> 00:33:48.290
and they'll
accidentally unencrypt--

00:33:48.290 --> 00:33:49.800
or they'll accidentally
encrypt it the wrong way,

00:33:49.800 --> 00:33:50.750
and it doesn't work,
and then you'll

00:33:50.750 --> 00:33:52.740
see them frantically
uploading a new file,

00:33:52.740 --> 00:33:54.800
like 30 minutes later.

00:33:54.800 --> 00:33:57.090
So there's a human
element involved.

00:33:57.090 --> 00:34:00.760
And I think providing
more insight

00:34:00.760 --> 00:34:04.320
is this recent Reuters
story where they interview

00:34:04.320 --> 00:34:07.710
actual censors-- human censors--
who work at these facilities.

00:34:07.710 --> 00:34:09.920
This one was in Tianjin
outside Beijing.

00:34:09.920 --> 00:34:12.380
And they said that there
was something close

00:34:12.380 --> 00:34:15.889
several thousand censors
who work in a facility.

00:34:15.889 --> 00:34:17.409
They work in shifts.

00:34:17.409 --> 00:34:19.739
They work in 10-hour
shifts, and folks come in

00:34:19.739 --> 00:34:22.690
and they-- but they do have
automated tools to help

00:34:22.690 --> 00:34:26.460
them identify and flag
sensitive key words.

00:34:26.460 --> 00:34:29.020
So there is computer
assistance involved.

00:34:29.020 --> 00:34:30.929
There are algorithms
that they've written,

00:34:30.929 --> 00:34:32.470
and they're constantly
getting better

00:34:32.470 --> 00:34:37.647
in helping the human censors do
their job is more thoroughly.

00:34:37.647 --> 00:34:40.629
AUDIENCE: So in the Workers
Revolution [INAUDIBLE],

00:34:40.629 --> 00:34:42.120
one of the things
they did is they

00:34:42.120 --> 00:34:46.172
did absurd things because it
would make the government feel

00:34:46.172 --> 00:34:47.558
stupid to crack down on it.

00:34:47.558 --> 00:34:51.781
They would meet in the square
[INAUDIBLE] that kind of thing.

00:34:51.781 --> 00:34:54.560
You couldn't arrest people
for eating ice cream.

00:34:54.560 --> 00:34:56.899
This workplace seems
absurd in the same way,

00:34:56.899 --> 00:34:59.060
but Chinese government
seems to have

00:34:59.060 --> 00:35:03.778
less of a worry about being
seen being silly or something.

00:35:03.778 --> 00:35:04.770
I don't know.

00:35:04.770 --> 00:35:09.730
Could you comment on
that difference in that

00:35:09.730 --> 00:35:12.954
the use of absurdism
versus blocking what

00:35:12.954 --> 00:35:14.674
seems like silly things.

00:35:14.674 --> 00:35:16.674
JASON Q. NG: Yeah, like
I said with the question

00:35:16.674 --> 00:35:20.980
before about how do
internet users walk

00:35:20.980 --> 00:35:23.100
that fine line between
communicating to everyone,

00:35:23.100 --> 00:35:25.865
and also still
evading the censors?

00:35:25.865 --> 00:35:27.740
And one of the ways they
do it is with humor,

00:35:27.740 --> 00:35:30.230
with funny images, which memes,
with sort of these inside

00:35:30.230 --> 00:35:30.730
jokes.

00:35:30.730 --> 00:35:35.490
So for instance,
back in recently

00:35:35.490 --> 00:35:37.700
for the June 4th commemoration,
which takes place

00:35:37.700 --> 00:35:39.158
every year in China,
internet users

00:35:39.158 --> 00:35:41.215
actually posted an
image of the tank man,

00:35:41.215 --> 00:35:43.590
but they were placed all the
tanks with this giant rubber

00:35:43.590 --> 00:35:44.600
duck.

00:35:44.600 --> 00:35:48.310
So you had four giant rubber
ducks facing off against a guy.

00:35:48.310 --> 00:35:52.170
So that's absurd and silly,
and for the government

00:35:52.170 --> 00:35:56.550
to crack down on that would
sort of be a statement about how

00:35:56.550 --> 00:36:00.470
they're maybe not just
not in favor of discussion

00:36:00.470 --> 00:36:04.590
of political sensitive content,
but also not in favor of humor.

00:36:04.590 --> 00:36:06.890
So that's one method.

00:36:06.890 --> 00:36:10.900
But yeah, it's
obviously a similar--

00:36:10.900 --> 00:36:13.860
it's a topic that, I think,
internet users have recognized,

00:36:13.860 --> 00:36:16.470
that you don't purposely--
you don't punch

00:36:16.470 --> 00:36:18.350
the government in
the face perhaps.

00:36:18.350 --> 00:36:20.683
They've learned that that's
not a very effective tactic.

00:36:20.683 --> 00:36:22.540
We've seen from Liu
Xiaobo, other folks who

00:36:22.540 --> 00:36:26.090
go out there directly
promoting political change.

00:36:26.090 --> 00:36:29.890
They tend to get dragged
in, and that perhaps

00:36:29.890 --> 00:36:31.880
isn't an effective tactic.

00:36:31.880 --> 00:36:34.540
So what they do is they
organize things like everyone

00:36:34.540 --> 00:36:36.290
wears a black t-shirt
on a particular day.

00:36:36.290 --> 00:36:37.664
They go out and
walk the streets.

00:36:37.664 --> 00:36:38.720
They take a stroll.

00:36:38.720 --> 00:36:41.400
That's [SPEAKING CHINESE],
which is their method

00:36:41.400 --> 00:36:44.190
for, I guess the sort of
eating ice cream in the square.

00:36:44.190 --> 00:36:53.400
So I think both methods are
supremely important in terms

00:36:53.400 --> 00:36:56.340
of fermenting change
in China and progress.

00:36:56.340 --> 00:36:58.030
You need serious
political activists,

00:36:58.030 --> 00:37:00.860
but you also need these sort
of light-hearted attempts

00:37:00.860 --> 00:37:04.921
to sort of show how ludicrous
some of the censorship system

00:37:04.921 --> 00:37:05.420
is.

00:37:08.738 --> 00:37:12.450
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] groups.

00:37:12.450 --> 00:37:14.890
Is data available to do
your kind of analysis

00:37:14.890 --> 00:37:17.575
on something like
that, like QQ groups

00:37:17.575 --> 00:37:20.324
and QQ instant messaging,
that sort of stuff.

00:37:20.324 --> 00:37:21.740
JASON Q. NG: Yeah,
QQ is another--

00:37:21.740 --> 00:37:25.660
the question was about, can we
also track censorship on QQ,

00:37:25.660 --> 00:37:27.764
which is a chat
client within China.

00:37:27.764 --> 00:37:29.430
I checked, that's
used around the world,

00:37:29.430 --> 00:37:33.460
but it's created by a Chinese
chat company called Tencent.

00:37:33.460 --> 00:37:37.640
So yeah, it's
actually interesting.

00:37:37.640 --> 00:37:42.130
One of the first real major
censorship gold mines--

00:37:42.130 --> 00:37:45.220
or for censorship
researchers-- was actually,

00:37:45.220 --> 00:37:48.120
I think it was late 1990s,
or-- I forget when it was.

00:37:48.120 --> 00:37:52.560
But hackers actually
figured out that QQ

00:37:52.560 --> 00:37:57.202
was storing on your computer
a certain file that basically

00:37:57.202 --> 00:37:59.410
every time you typed
information in your chat window,

00:37:59.410 --> 00:38:00.868
it would compare
it with this file.

00:38:00.868 --> 00:38:02.940
And if anything was
contained in that file,

00:38:02.940 --> 00:38:04.660
they would actually
censor your content.

00:38:04.660 --> 00:38:07.860
So hackers actually
extracted the keyword list,

00:38:07.860 --> 00:38:10.550
and actually shared that widely.

00:38:10.550 --> 00:38:13.090
And I think that was one the
first instances of reverse

00:38:13.090 --> 00:38:15.120
engineering the sort
of censorship that

00:38:15.120 --> 00:38:16.700
is built into these
sort of systems.

00:38:16.700 --> 00:38:21.880
So yeah, there's definitely
researchers who are actively

00:38:21.880 --> 00:38:24.890
looking into various ways
that chat clients, like QQ

00:38:24.890 --> 00:38:28.530
and WeChat and
other social media,

00:38:28.530 --> 00:38:31.550
are actively censoring
and surveilling users.

00:38:31.550 --> 00:38:34.388
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] you
have on the effectiveness,

00:38:34.388 --> 00:38:37.940
because it seems like
for all their censorship,

00:38:37.940 --> 00:38:42.530
it may block some casual
users, but between all

00:38:42.530 --> 00:38:45.169
the evasions and all the
way people rephrase things,

00:38:45.169 --> 00:38:47.210
you said that basically--
the Red Cross incident,

00:38:47.210 --> 00:38:49.535
they blocked a key
word, but it's still

00:38:49.535 --> 00:38:52.020
affecting their
donations by 50%.

00:38:52.020 --> 00:38:54.870
So does it seem like the
information is stilling

00:38:54.870 --> 00:38:56.370
getting out to a
majority of people,

00:38:56.370 --> 00:39:00.330
or is it only the ones who are
in the know, or [INAUDIBLE]?

00:39:00.330 --> 00:39:01.080
JASON Q. NG: Yeah.

00:39:01.080 --> 00:39:05.350
The question was
about how effective

00:39:05.350 --> 00:39:07.770
do we actually think
these sort of blocking

00:39:07.770 --> 00:39:12.885
and censorship is, because
based on what we've seen,

00:39:12.885 --> 00:39:14.760
internet users are able
to evade the censors.

00:39:14.760 --> 00:39:20.760
So I think the answer is that--
or I think one way to look at

00:39:20.760 --> 00:39:24.012
is that we only know about
certain-- like for instance,

00:39:24.012 --> 00:39:24.970
the Red Cross incident.

00:39:24.970 --> 00:39:28.070
We know about that incident,
but what about the many dozens--

00:39:28.070 --> 00:39:30.580
or for each of those
cases, many dozens of cases

00:39:30.580 --> 00:39:32.010
that we don't know about?

00:39:32.010 --> 00:39:34.260
So we may just have a
little tip of the iceberg.

00:39:34.260 --> 00:39:37.084
We can see these sorts of
ways where internet users

00:39:37.084 --> 00:39:38.750
were able to evade
the censors, and were

00:39:38.750 --> 00:39:41.580
able to produce a
profound change.

00:39:41.580 --> 00:39:46.516
But the whole point of
censorship is that it's obtuse.

00:39:46.516 --> 00:39:47.890
We'll never find
out, we'll never

00:39:47.890 --> 00:39:51.064
know unless more research
gets done, someone

00:39:51.064 --> 00:39:52.980
releases this information,
that sort of thing.

00:39:52.980 --> 00:39:57.050
So based on other
researcher people

00:39:57.050 --> 00:40:00.590
have done, there's a study
by [? Yu ?] and Robinson

00:40:00.590 --> 00:40:06.210
where they look into why people
actually want to evade censors

00:40:06.210 --> 00:40:10.552
or why would people want to
escape restrictions in China.

00:40:10.552 --> 00:40:12.010
And for the most
part, folks aren't

00:40:12.010 --> 00:40:15.156
interested in engaging
in political activism.

00:40:15.156 --> 00:40:16.780
Folks are really
pretty much interested

00:40:16.780 --> 00:40:18.890
in just getting a stable
internet connection,

00:40:18.890 --> 00:40:20.400
getting access to information.

00:40:20.400 --> 00:40:23.610
And so based on
that sort of thing,

00:40:23.610 --> 00:40:26.850
you get the sense that Chinese
internet users, the majority

00:40:26.850 --> 00:40:29.320
of them are, for the
most part, satisfied

00:40:29.320 --> 00:40:33.580
with the sort of material
that they have online.

00:40:33.580 --> 00:40:36.167
They don't have
YouTube, but they Youku.

00:40:36.167 --> 00:40:37.750
Instead of Facebook,
they have Yunyun.

00:40:37.750 --> 00:40:41.260
So this sort of thing,
I think, appears

00:40:41.260 --> 00:40:43.670
to be taking place in China.

00:40:43.670 --> 00:40:45.900
But obviously, there
are hardcore, dedicated

00:40:45.900 --> 00:40:49.074
folks who are focused on
expanding freedom of expression

00:40:49.074 --> 00:40:50.490
in China, making
sure that there's

00:40:50.490 --> 00:40:52.190
social justice, and
that sort of thing.

00:40:52.190 --> 00:40:57.605
And they do play a large
role in the social sphere.

00:40:57.605 --> 00:41:00.455
AUDIENCE: So your research seems
to be about the content that's

00:41:00.455 --> 00:41:02.355
censored, but how
about the people.

00:41:02.355 --> 00:41:06.350
Are they anonymous on
these social networks?

00:41:06.350 --> 00:41:07.270
Are they tracked?

00:41:07.270 --> 00:41:08.130
Are they surveilled?

00:41:08.130 --> 00:41:11.850
Do they feel like they
may get in trouble

00:41:11.850 --> 00:41:13.160
if post certain [INAUDIBLE]?

00:41:13.160 --> 00:41:15.510
JASON Q. NG: Yeah.

00:41:15.510 --> 00:41:18.915
Yeah, so the question was
about-- this is about content

00:41:18.915 --> 00:41:21.040
that's being blocked, but
what about the people who

00:41:21.040 --> 00:41:22.123
post this sort of content.

00:41:22.123 --> 00:41:23.540
Do they fear for their lives?

00:41:23.540 --> 00:41:26.180
Are there sort of ways for
the government to track them?

00:41:26.180 --> 00:41:27.570
And the answer is yes.

00:41:27.570 --> 00:41:33.850
Social media in China--
technically, for some time,

00:41:33.850 --> 00:41:36.950
the government's imposed a
rule where social media had

00:41:36.950 --> 00:41:39.500
to require that people their
real names to register.

00:41:39.500 --> 00:41:44.770
So obviously, there are
loopholes to get around it.

00:41:44.770 --> 00:41:50.040
So one of the ways that real
name registration required

00:41:50.040 --> 00:41:51.260
was using your cell phone.

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:53.450
So sometimes, people would use
just throwaway cell phones,

00:41:53.450 --> 00:41:54.283
and stuff like that.

00:41:54.283 --> 00:41:56.870
But in theory,
technically every cell

00:41:56.870 --> 00:41:58.900
phone that you sign
up for, technically

00:41:58.900 --> 00:42:03.200
the vendor is supposed to have
your actual real information.

00:42:03.200 --> 00:42:10.070
But that's China, or any
country where this sort of thing

00:42:10.070 --> 00:42:13.580
is just like, come on, you're
really going to-- yeah.

00:42:13.580 --> 00:42:17.232
So this has been a major issue,
especially with over the past

00:42:17.232 --> 00:42:18.690
several months and
over the summer,

00:42:18.690 --> 00:42:22.530
wherein Weibo and other social
media have been targeting these

00:42:22.530 --> 00:42:26.630
so-called big V's-- these
verified users on Weibo who are

00:42:26.630 --> 00:42:27.410
these celebrities.

00:42:27.410 --> 00:42:29.050
They have millions of followers.

00:42:29.050 --> 00:42:30.740
They are very powerful.

00:42:30.740 --> 00:42:32.920
They're the power
users of Weibo.

00:42:32.920 --> 00:42:34.740
And they're known publicly.

00:42:34.740 --> 00:42:39.440
They're intellectuals, scholars,
activists, lawyers, but also

00:42:39.440 --> 00:42:41.700
just like actors and
actresses, and stuff like that.

00:42:41.700 --> 00:42:44.670
So we've seen
that-- and actually,

00:42:44.670 --> 00:42:49.140
in March the Head of the State
Internet Information Office

00:42:49.140 --> 00:42:52.970
actually brought in all of these
bunch of big V's, and actually

00:42:52.970 --> 00:42:54.100
had dinner with them.

00:42:54.100 --> 00:42:56.210
He called them in, sat
them down, and said,

00:42:56.210 --> 00:42:59.380
look, we need to make sure
that social media in the future

00:42:59.380 --> 00:43:01.880
isn't filled with rumors, isn't
filled with malicious lies.

00:43:01.880 --> 00:43:03.713
We have to make sure
that what we're posting

00:43:03.713 --> 00:43:08.490
is supportive of the
health of society.

00:43:08.490 --> 00:43:11.250
So people got the message.

00:43:11.250 --> 00:43:14.344
And over the summer actually,
there was a big crack down,

00:43:14.344 --> 00:43:16.510
and a lot of these big V's
were actually dragged in.

00:43:16.510 --> 00:43:21.020
There was one economic
writer, Charles Xue,

00:43:21.020 --> 00:43:22.190
was actually brought in.

00:43:22.190 --> 00:43:24.790
He had to do this
forced confession.

00:43:24.790 --> 00:43:27.040
There are other folks who
have been arrested recently.

00:43:27.040 --> 00:43:29.170
So it's clear that
the government

00:43:29.170 --> 00:43:31.650
is very interested in
targeting individuals, as well,

00:43:31.650 --> 00:43:33.357
in addition to
censoring content.

00:43:36.339 --> 00:43:39.818
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
it seems that China

00:43:39.818 --> 00:43:43.048
has its own version
of Twitter and things

00:43:43.048 --> 00:43:46.470
that Youku for YouTube
and Baidu for Google.

00:43:46.470 --> 00:43:49.810
How much urgency do you
sense from Chinese users

00:43:49.810 --> 00:43:54.993
to use the Western generated
products versus use their own,

00:43:54.993 --> 00:43:57.300
and have more
censorship on them.

00:43:57.300 --> 00:43:59.554
Because I don't
sense a lot of need

00:43:59.554 --> 00:44:07.610
to use Google over Baidu but it
obviously [INAUDIBLE] search.

00:44:07.610 --> 00:44:08.360
JASON Q. NG: Yeah.

00:44:08.360 --> 00:44:11.050
Obviously, there are
hardcore folks within China

00:44:11.050 --> 00:44:14.650
who are very adamant about using
products that aren't censored.

00:44:14.650 --> 00:44:16.369
So when Google did
pull out of China,

00:44:16.369 --> 00:44:18.660
you had people laying wreaths
and flowers at the Google

00:44:18.660 --> 00:44:21.770
Office, because they were
really saddened by the fact

00:44:21.770 --> 00:44:25.210
that a company like
Google left China,

00:44:25.210 --> 00:44:27.080
and now they were
forced to use products

00:44:27.080 --> 00:44:29.510
like Baidu-- which if
you haven't used Baidu,

00:44:29.510 --> 00:44:31.570
it's actually a pretty
good search tool

00:44:31.570 --> 00:44:34.910
so long as you're not searching
for sensitive content.

00:44:34.910 --> 00:44:43.590
So I think there are folks who
are very, very much into using

00:44:43.590 --> 00:44:45.180
Twitter and YouTube
from within China.

00:44:45.180 --> 00:44:47.040
And the thing is,
for the most part,

00:44:47.040 --> 00:44:50.400
if you want to use Twitter
and Facebook within China,

00:44:50.400 --> 00:44:52.970
you have the tools to allow
you to get access to them.

00:44:52.970 --> 00:44:54.784
It's not like Iran
where sometimes they

00:44:54.784 --> 00:44:56.200
throttle the
internet to the point

00:44:56.200 --> 00:44:58.320
where you can't use YouTube.

00:44:58.320 --> 00:45:01.310
You could actually
use-- well, now VPN's

00:45:01.310 --> 00:45:03.344
a little more dicey
since it's harder to get.

00:45:03.344 --> 00:45:05.260
It's a good, solid VPN
that works for a while.

00:45:05.260 --> 00:45:08.450
But you can use various
types of circumvention tools

00:45:08.450 --> 00:45:10.650
to get access to YouTube,
Facebook, Twitter

00:45:10.650 --> 00:45:12.990
from within China
if you want to.

00:45:12.990 --> 00:45:14.984
The thing is, most
folks-- why go

00:45:14.984 --> 00:45:16.900
on Twitter when all your
friends are on Weibo?

00:45:16.900 --> 00:45:20.240
It's network effect, so
it's fairly entrenched

00:45:20.240 --> 00:45:24.620
at this point, Weibo and
other sorts of social media.

00:45:24.620 --> 00:45:27.920
So I think for the most
part, Chinese internet users,

00:45:27.920 --> 00:45:30.910
some of them may actually
use domestic products out

00:45:30.910 --> 00:45:31.950
of patriotism.

00:45:31.950 --> 00:45:39.880
For the most, I think folks are
just-- not necessarily lazy,

00:45:39.880 --> 00:45:42.000
but that's the
thing that loads up

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:46.339
when they can start their
computer, that's what they use.

00:45:46.339 --> 00:45:48.380
AUDIENCE: Just to follow
up about on the question

00:45:48.380 --> 00:45:50.348
about people versus content.

00:45:50.348 --> 00:45:59.470
The way for the content
creators side [INAUDIBLE],

00:45:59.470 --> 00:46:01.410
is there any sense,
especially given

00:46:01.410 --> 00:46:03.587
that it's not just
the China-- you

00:46:03.587 --> 00:46:06.545
see global [INAUDIBLE]
metadata, data mining,

00:46:06.545 --> 00:46:09.496
and query analysis post facto.

00:46:09.496 --> 00:46:12.520
Is there any sense or
precedent that China

00:46:12.520 --> 00:46:17.000
might be saving query
traffic across all users

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:22.960
to find who searched
for certain [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:22.960 --> 00:46:24.430
browsing activity [INAUDIBLE]?

00:46:28.580 --> 00:46:29.330
JASON Q. NG: Sure.

00:46:29.330 --> 00:46:31.280
So the question was--
again, going back

00:46:31.280 --> 00:46:36.400
to whether the government
is tracking people

00:46:36.400 --> 00:46:39.040
with regards, especially
to sucking up metadata,

00:46:39.040 --> 00:46:41.990
and whether or not
we think companies

00:46:41.990 --> 00:46:45.930
like Sina or the government
are using this sort of metadata

00:46:45.930 --> 00:46:50.020
as a way to figure out
who should be brought in

00:46:50.020 --> 00:46:51.500
for questioning.

00:46:51.500 --> 00:46:56.720
So I certainly
don't have knowledge

00:46:56.720 --> 00:47:01.080
of metadata being used
in this sort of fashion.

00:47:01.080 --> 00:47:04.880
I think from the sort
of anecdotal evidence

00:47:04.880 --> 00:47:08.640
that we have, it's more
straight surveillance.

00:47:08.640 --> 00:47:12.840
If they know that
your a activist,

00:47:12.840 --> 00:47:16.220
they may get access to
your WeChat account,

00:47:16.220 --> 00:47:18.570
and then start tracking
the messages you post.

00:47:18.570 --> 00:47:20.080
And then when you
say, oh, I'm going

00:47:20.080 --> 00:47:22.500
to be having lunch at
the Chaoyang Square

00:47:22.500 --> 00:47:26.827
or whatever, they send an
officer who follows you.

00:47:26.827 --> 00:47:28.410
And then you get
there, and you notice

00:47:28.410 --> 00:47:30.910
how the officer is there, and
you wonder how they got there.

00:47:30.910 --> 00:47:33.550
So that's the sort of thing
that I think their method

00:47:33.550 --> 00:47:39.710
for tracking sensitive people.

00:47:39.710 --> 00:47:44.870
As for figuring out-- from
the vast, big data who

00:47:44.870 --> 00:47:46.460
might be terrorists
or whatever--

00:47:46.460 --> 00:47:48.680
I'm sure that their
equivalent of the NSA

00:47:48.680 --> 00:47:52.610
is doing the same sort of thing
that the NSA is doing here.

00:47:52.610 --> 00:47:56.710
But I don't know if individual
netizens who are just,

00:47:56.710 --> 00:47:58.380
like, looking at
pornography online

00:47:58.380 --> 00:48:00.782
should be worried that
they're metadata's

00:48:00.782 --> 00:48:02.740
going to be sucked up,
and then somehow they're

00:48:02.740 --> 00:48:04.170
going to end up in prison.

00:48:04.170 --> 00:48:07.850
I think the Chinese
authorities--

00:48:07.850 --> 00:48:09.800
they're efficient.

00:48:09.800 --> 00:48:11.820
They know who they
should be focused on,

00:48:11.820 --> 00:48:16.150
and I think that's not
their primary target.

00:48:16.150 --> 00:48:17.970
Yeah?

00:48:17.970 --> 00:48:21.510
AUDIENCE: A question just
referring to China's NSA,

00:48:21.510 --> 00:48:23.140
and we haven't really
talked much about

00:48:23.140 --> 00:48:27.400
who [INAUDIBLE] this censorship.

00:48:27.400 --> 00:48:31.676
I wonder if they're
just concentrated solely

00:48:31.676 --> 00:48:35.210
in the Propaganda Ministry
that has controls on this?

00:48:35.210 --> 00:48:39.030
Or are there multiple
agencies or groups

00:48:39.030 --> 00:48:41.284
that are involved censorship
in China, from what

00:48:41.284 --> 00:48:43.530
you can infer from
your research?

00:48:43.530 --> 00:48:44.280
JASON Q. NG: Yeah.

00:48:44.280 --> 00:48:45.630
So the question was
about who's actually

00:48:45.630 --> 00:48:47.713
performing the sort of
censorship, what government

00:48:47.713 --> 00:48:50.420
agencies and/or
folks are involved.

00:48:50.420 --> 00:48:53.170
And clearly, yeah,
it's something

00:48:53.170 --> 00:48:55.230
that's politically
driven in some ways.

00:48:55.230 --> 00:49:00.120
So you have this new bureau
called the State Internet

00:49:00.120 --> 00:49:02.160
Information Office,
which is sort

00:49:02.160 --> 00:49:05.240
of an offshoot of the State
Council Information Office,

00:49:05.240 --> 00:49:09.870
which is now supposedly the
lead figure for performing

00:49:09.870 --> 00:49:11.360
this sort of
information control.

00:49:11.360 --> 00:49:12.985
But you have all
these other ministries

00:49:12.985 --> 00:49:15.670
and bureaucracies
that are involved.

00:49:15.670 --> 00:49:18.260
But you also have not just
these multiple agencies

00:49:18.260 --> 00:49:20.600
and bureaucracies, but you
also to notice that there's

00:49:20.600 --> 00:49:22.697
a national level of
information control,

00:49:22.697 --> 00:49:25.030
but then you also have local
officials who are involved.

00:49:25.030 --> 00:49:26.790
You have police,
security bureaus,

00:49:26.790 --> 00:49:29.850
and other folks who have
different interests than maybe

00:49:29.850 --> 00:49:32.890
the national agents.

00:49:32.890 --> 00:49:35.325
So you have these
different layers.

00:49:35.325 --> 00:49:36.700
And then you throw
into that, you

00:49:36.700 --> 00:49:42.220
have private companies who have
a vested interest in preventing

00:49:42.220 --> 00:49:45.070
any sort of potentially even
sensitive discussion taking

00:49:45.070 --> 00:49:46.100
place on their site.

00:49:46.100 --> 00:49:48.140
So you have another layer
of censorship there,

00:49:48.140 --> 00:49:50.015
and then you have the
actual users themselves

00:49:50.015 --> 00:49:53.730
who have to self-censor,
who actually report

00:49:53.730 --> 00:49:55.910
on other users who are
posting provocative content.

00:49:55.910 --> 00:49:57.680
So you have these
multiple layers,

00:49:57.680 --> 00:50:00.950
and it's not very clear.

00:50:00.950 --> 00:50:05.110
It's not as simple as they're
doing it, or it's them.

00:50:05.110 --> 00:50:08.540
It's very much a de-centralized,
diffused censorship system,

00:50:08.540 --> 00:50:12.920
which is, I think, a feature
of the Chinese system.

00:50:15.510 --> 00:50:19.460
All right, I think
everyone is too scared,

00:50:19.460 --> 00:50:20.883
and we're going
to call it quits.

00:50:20.883 --> 00:50:23.190
All right, thanks so
much everyone for--

00:50:23.190 --> 00:50:28.206
[APPLAUSE]

